rents, teachers, and young people alike; and places children and family reading networks into the context of debates on the history of childhood, and the history of the book. Merridee L. Bailey is a social and cultural historian of late medieval and early modern England. She is an Associate Member of the Facultyof History, University of Oxford.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild development -- England -- History -- To 1500 -- Sources. 0aChildren -- Great Britain -- History -- To 1500. 0aSocialization -- England -- History -- To 1500 -- Sources. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChild.  aCourtesy poems.  aGuidance.  aHistory of childhood.  aMedieval England.  aPedagogic books.  aSocialization.  aVernacular literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204060640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782040606423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782040606/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles